	<p class="eyebrow">Food &amp; local cuisine</p>
	<h1>What you'll <span class="accent">eat</span></h1>
	<p class="tagline">
		Valencia invented paella. Gandía invented fideuá. The rest of the table is
		fresh fish, good olive oil and a glass of something cold.
	</p>

	<p>
		This stretch of coast is one of the great eating regions of Spain. The
		dishes are simple, generous and built around what's grown or pulled out of
		the sea that morning: short-grain rice from the Albufera wetlands, almonds
		and olive oil from the inland sierras, tomatoes and peppers from the
		valley huertas, fish from Dénia, Cullera and the little ports along the
		coast.
	</p>

	<figure>
		<img src="/images/paella-valenciana.jpg" alt="A traditional paella valenciana cooked in a wide pan — saffron-yellow rice with chicken, rabbit and green beans." />
		<figcaption>Paella valenciana — the original, born in the Valencia <em>huerta</em>.</figcaption>
	</figure>

	<p>
		<strong>Paella valenciana</strong> is the dish the region is built on — the
		original, with chicken, rabbit, snails, garrofó and ferradura beans, cooked
		over fire in a wide flat pan until the bottom forms <em>socarrat</em>, the
		caramelised rice crust everyone fights over. Order it for lunch, never
		dinner, and never on Sundays without booking ahead.
	</p>

	<p>
		<strong>Fideuá</strong> is Gandía's own dish — paella's seafood cousin, made
		with short toasted noodles instead of rice, simmered in fish broth with
		prawns, squid and monkfish, finished with a swipe of garlic
		<em>allioli</em>. Local sailors invented it on a fishing boat south of
		town in the 1900s. Gandía is to fideuá what Valencia is to paella.
	</p>

	<p>
		Beyond the rice pan, the regional table runs to <strong>arroz a banda</strong>
		(rice cooked in fish stock), <strong>arroz negro</strong> (stained black
		with squid ink), <strong>all i pebre</strong> (a smoky eel-and-garlic stew
		from the Albufera lagoon), the famously sweet <strong>gamba roja de Dénia</strong>,
		coca flatbreads, <em>esgarraet</em> of salt cod and roasted pepper, and
		mid-afternoon <strong>horchata with fartons</strong> — the cold tigernut
		drink served with sugar-glazed fingers of brioche.
	</p>

	<figure>
		<img src="/images/chivito-foto.jpg" alt="A round of bocadillos at the table — hands holding up baguettes, one rubbed with fresh tomato, another opened to show grilled pork and melted cheese, with a side salad on a plate." />
	</figure>

	<p>
		Spanish meals run late, so the gap between lunch and dinner is bridged by
		<strong>la merienda</strong> — a small late-afternoon bite, usually around
		six. The classic merienda is a <strong>bocadillo</strong>: a length of
		baguette split open and packed with chorizo, jamón serrano, tortilla,
		manchego, fried calamari, or pork lomo with bacon, cheese and a fried egg
		— the <strong>chivito</strong>, the quintessentially Valencian bocadillo.
		Beach kiosks make them all summer; village bakeries make better ones for
		half the price. It's the meal that keeps Spaniards going from siesta to a
		10 p.m. dinner.
	</p>

	<p class="pull">
		Tell us how you like to eat, and we'll book the table.
	</p>

	<p>
		Travellers eat differently. Some want a long, slow lunch at a
		<em>chiringuito</em> on the sand, paella for four and a bottle of cold
		rosé. Others want a Michelin-listed kitchen with a sea view, or a
		family-run <em>casa de comidas</em> in the old town where the menu's on a
		chalkboard. Vegetarians, vegans, gluten-free, kids who only want pasta —
		the Valencian coast handles all of it well, and we know which kitchens do
		each one properly.
	</p>

	<p>
		<strong>Tell us what you like to eat — and what you don't.</strong> We'll
